        "# Function\n",
        "\n",
        "            Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        "Question 1: What is the difference between K-Means and Hierarchical Clustering?Provide a use case for each.\n",
        "\n",
        "Ans Difference between K-Means and Hierarchical Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        "Aspect  K-Means Clustering  Hierarchical Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        "Approach    Partition-based (divides data into K clusters)  Tree-based (creates a hierarchy of clusters in a dendrogram)\n",
        "Input Requirement   Requires pre-defining number of clusters (K)    No need to predefine clusters; can decide by cutting the dendrogram\n",
        "Computation Faster, works well on large datasets    Slower, expensive on large datasets (O(n²))\n",
        "Cluster Shape   Works well for spherical, equally sized clusters    Can capture complex, nested cluster structures\n",
        "Result  Flat clustering (non-overlapping clusters)  Hierarchical clustering (nested clusters, relationships visible)\n",
        "Scalability Very scalable for large datasets    Not scalable for big datasets (best for small/medium data)\n",
        "\n",
        "Use Cases\n",
        "\n",
        "1. K-Means Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        "Use Case: Market segmentation in retail.\n",
        "Example: A supermarket wants to group customers into 5 segments based on their purchase behavior. K-Means is ideal since the number of segments (K=5) is predefined and the dataset is large.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Hierarchical Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        "Use Case: Document or gene classification.\n",
        "Example: A biologist wants to analyze genetic similarity between 50 species. Hierarchical clustering helps visualize relationships in a dendrogram, making it easier to see evolutionary closeness without fixing the number of clusters.\n",
        "\n",
        "Question 2: Explain the purpose of the Silhouette Score in evaluating clustering algorithms.\n",
        "\n",
        "Ans Silhouette Score in Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        "The Silhouette Score is a metric to evaluate the quality of clusters formed by a clustering algorithm. It measures how well each data point fits within its assigned cluster compared to other clusters.\n",
        "\n",
        "Formula\n",
        "\n",
        "For a single point i:\n",
        "\n",
        "S(i) = \\frac{b(i) - a(i)}{\\max(a(i), b(i))}\n",
        "\n",
        "Where:\n",
        "\n",
        "a(i) = Average distance of point i to other points in the same cluster (intra-cluster distance).\n",
        "\n",
        "b(i) = Average distance of point i to the nearest cluster (inter-cluster distance).\n",
        "\n",
        "Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "+1 (close to 1) → Point is well-clustered (assigned to the right cluster).\n",
        "\n",
        "0 → Point lies between two clusters (boundary case).\n",
        "\n",
        "-1 (close to -1) → Point is likely misclassified (assigned to wrong cluster).\n",
        "\n",
        "The overall Silhouette Score is the average of all points’ scores.\n",
        "\n",
        "Purpose\n",
        "\n",
        "Validates clustering quality without ground truth labels.\n",
        "\n",
        "Helps select the optimal number of clusters (K) in K-Means.\n",
        "\n",
        "Detects poorly defined clusters or misclassifications.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example\n",
        "\n",
        "If you run K-Means with K = 2, 3, 4 …\n",
        "\n",
        "You calculate Silhouette Score for each.\n",
        "\n",
        "The K with the highest score is usually the best choice (clusters are dense & well separated).\n",
        "\n",
        "Question 3: What are the core parameters of DBSCAN, and how do they influence the clustering process?\n",
        "\n",
        "Ans DBSCAN (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) mainly depends on two core parameters:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. ε (Epsilon / eps)\n",
        "\n",
        "Definition: The maximum radius of the neighborhood around a point.\n",
        "\n",
        "Influence:\n",
        "\n",
        "A small eps → many points may be considered as noise (outliers), and clusters may be very small or fragmented.\n",
        "\n",
        "A large eps → clusters may merge together, leading to fewer, larger clusters (sometimes even one big cluster).\n",
        "\n",
        "Key role: Defines the density reachability – i.e., how close points must be to each other to be considered neighbors.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. MinPts (Minimum Points)\n",
        "\n",
        "Definition: The minimum number of points required within the eps radius for a point to be considered a core point.\n",
        "\n",
        "Influence:\n",
        "\n",
        "Small MinPts (e.g., 2 or 3) → even sparse regions can form clusters, possibly creating many small/unwanted clusters.\n",
        "\n",
        "Large MinPts → requires higher density to form clusters, which makes the algorithm stricter; more points may be labeled as noise.\n",
        "\n",
        "Rule of thumb: Often set to MinPts ≥ D + 1, where D = number of dimensions.\n",
        "\n",
        "How they work together\n",
        "\n",
        "Core Point: A point with at least MinPts neighbors within distance eps.\n",
        "\n",
        "Border Point: Has fewer than MinPts neighbors within eps but lies within the neighborhood of a core point.\n",
        "\n",
        "Noise Point: Not a core point and not reachable from any core point.\n",
        "\n",
        "Question 4: Why is feature scaling important when applying clustering algorithms like K-Means and DBSCAN?\n",
        "\n",
        "Ans Feature scaling is very important when applying clustering algorithms like K-Means and DBSCAN because both algorithms rely heavily on distance calculations (usually Euclidean distance). If features are on different scales, the clustering results can become biased.\n",
        "\n",
        "Here’s why:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Distance Dominance Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose one feature is in the range [0, 1] (e.g., probability) and another is in the range [0, 10,000] (e.g., annual income).\n",
        "\n",
        "When calculating distances, the large-scale feature will dominate the computation, making the small-scale feature almost irrelevant.\n",
        "\n",
        "This leads to distorted clusters.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. K-Means Sensitivity\n",
        "\n",
        "K Means assigns points to clusters based on the closest centroid.\n",
        "\n",
        "If features are not scaled, centroids will be pulled toward features with larger values, and clusters will not represent the true structure of the data.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. DBSCAN Sensitivity\n",
        "\n",
        "DBSCAN uses ε (eps) to decide neighborhood radius.\n",
        "\n",
        "If features are on different scales, choosing a meaningful ε becomes nearly impossible.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example: In a dataset with \"height (cm)\" and \"income ($)\", income will dominate distance, so clusters may form based on income alone, ignoring height.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. Better Interpretability\n",
        "\n",
        "Scaling ensures that each feature contributes equally to distance calculations.\n",
        "\n",
        "This way, the clusters reflect combined information from all features instead of being biased.\n",
        "\n",
        "Question 5: What is the Elbow Method in K-Means clustering and how does it help determine the optimal number of clusters?\n",
        "\n",
        "Ans Elbow Method in K-Means\n",
        "\n",
        "The Elbow Method is a visual technique to find the optimal number of clusters (K) in K-Means clustering.\n",
        "\n",
        "How it Works:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Run K-Means with different values of K (e.g., 1–10).\n",
        "\n",
        "2. For each K, compute the Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS) = how close data points are to their cluster centroids.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. Plot WCSS vs. K.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. As K increases, WCSS decreases (clusters fit better). But after a certain point, the improvement slows down.\n",
        "\n",
        "The “Elbow Point”:\n",
        "\n",
        "The graph looks like a bent arm.\n",
        "\n",
        "The point where the curve starts to flatten (like an elbow) is the optimal K.\n",
        "It represents the best balance between:\n",
        "Too few clusters (high error, underfitting)\n",
        "\n",
        "Too many clusters (overfitting, unnecessary complexity)"
      ],
      "metadata": {

      }

        "\n",
        "Question 6: Generate synthetic data using make_blobs(n_samples=300, centers=4),\n",
        "apply KMeans clustering, and visualize the results with cluster centers.\n",
        "\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate synthetic dataset with 4 centers\n",
        "X, y_true = make_blobs(n_samples=300, centers=4, cluster_std=0.60, random_state=42)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply KMeans clustering\n",
        "kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42)\n",
        "y_kmeans = kmeans.fit_predict(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Visualization of clusters with their centers\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
        "plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y_kmeans, s=50, cmap='viridis')\n",
        "centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_\n",
        "plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='red', s=200, alpha=0.75, marker='X', label='Centers')\n",
        "plt.title(\"KMeans Clustering with Cluster Centers\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Feature 1\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Feature 2\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],

        "\n",
        "Question 7: Load the Wine dataset, apply StandardScaler , and then train a DBSCAN\n",

        "\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import load_wine\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Load Wine dataset\n",
        "data = load_wine()\n",
        "X = data.data\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply StandardScaler\n",
        "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
        "X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Train DBSCAN model\n",
        "dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=1.8, min_samples=5)  # eps tuned for Wine dataset\n",
        "labels = dbscan.fit_predict(X_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Count clusters (excluding noise = label -1)\n",
        "n_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)\n",
        "n_noise = list(labels).count(-1)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Number of clusters found (excluding noise):\", n_clusters)\n",
        "print(\"Number of noise points:\", n_noise)"

        "Question 10: You are working as a data analyst at an e-commerce company. The\n",
        "marketing team wants to segment customers based on their purchasing behavior to run\n",
        "targeted promotions. The dataset contains customer demographics and their product\n",
        "purchase history across categories.\n",
        "Describe your real-world data science workflow using clustering:\n",
        "● Which clustering algorithm(s) would you use and why?\n",
        "● How would you preprocess the data (missing values, scaling)?\n",
        "● How would you determine the number of clusters?\n",
        "● How would the marketing team benefit from your clustering analysis?\n",
        "\n",
        "Ans 1. Choice of Clustering Algorithm(s)\n",
        "\n",
        "K-Means: Good for large datasets, efficient, works well when clusters are spherical.\n",
        "\n",
        "DBSCAN: Useful for finding arbitrary-shaped clusters and detecting outliers (e.g., unusual purchase behavior).\n",
        "\n",
        "Hierarchical Clustering: Good for smaller datasets when interpretability (dendrogram) is important.\n",
        "\n",
        "I would start with K-Means for segmentation, then validate with DBSCAN for outlier detection.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Preprocessing the Data\n",
        "\n",
        "Handle missing values:\n",
        "\n",
        "Fill demographic features with median/mode.\n",
        "\n",
        "Fill purchase amounts with 0 (if no purchase in a category).\n",
        "\n",
        "Encoding categorical variables (e.g., gender → one-hot encoding).\n",
        "\n",
        "Feature Scaling: Standardize features with StandardScaler to ensure equal contribution to clustering.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. Determine the Number of Clusters\n",
        "\n",
        "Use Elbow Method and Silhouette Score to decide the optimal K for K-Means.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. Marketing Team Benefits\n",
        "\n",
        "Identify high-value customers (target with premium offers).\n",
        "\n",
        "Detect bargain hunters (target with discounts).\n",
        "\n",
        "Segment by category preferences (personalized product recommendations).\n",
        "\n",
        "Spot inactive customers (reactivation campaigns)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "o4eQQApwQ0nd"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
        "from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- Step 1: Simulate e-commerce dataset ---\n",
        "np.random.seed(42)\n",
        "data = {\n",
        "    \"Age\": np.random.randint(18, 65, 200),\n",
        "    \"Annual_Income\": np.random.randint(20000, 100000, 200),\n",
        "    \"Spending_Score\": np.random.randint(1, 100, 200),\n",
        "    \"Electronics_Purchases\": np.random.randint(0, 20, 200),\n",
        "    \"Clothing_Purchases\": np.random.randint(0, 30, 200),\n",
        "    \"Grocery_Purchases\": np.random.randint(0, 50, 200)\n",
        "}\n",
        "df = pd.DataFrame(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- Step 2: Preprocessing ---\n",
        "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
        "X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df)\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- Step 3: Elbow Method to find optimal clusters ---\n",
        "wcss = []\n",
        "for k in range(2, 10):\n",
        "    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)\n",
        "    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)\n",
        "    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n",
        "plt.plot(range(2, 10), wcss, marker='o')\n",
        "plt.title(\"Elbow Method for Optimal K\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Number of clusters\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"WCSS\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- Step 4: Train KMeans with chosen K (say 4 from elbow curve) ---\n",
        "kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42)\n",
        "labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)\n",
        "df[\"Cluster\"] = labels\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- Step 5: Evaluate with Silhouette Score ---\n",
        "sil_score = silhouette_score(X_scaled, labels)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Silhouette Score:\", sil_score)\n",
        "print(df.groupby(\"Cluster\").mean())"
      ],
